00:02:02.831 --> 00:02:05.334 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Now, and when you
talk about controlling the human

00:02:05.334 --> 00:02:08.377 align:middle line:84%
mind, are we talking
about technology doing it?

00:02:08.377 --> 00:02:13.550 align:middle line:84%
Are we talking about just
doing it in terms of episodes

00:02:13.550 --> 00:02:17.054 align:middle line:84%
where you bombard people with
information and they change?

00:02:17.054 --> 00:02:18.263 align:middle line:90%
What's the concept here?

00:02:18.263 --> 00:02:19.723 align:middle line:84%
>>BEGICH: There's
a number of ways.

00:02:19.723 --> 00:02:21.600 align:middle line:84%
You're talking about
kind of the spectrum,

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:24.978 align:middle line:84%
from the propaganda
kind of approaches

00:02:24.978 --> 00:02:27.314 align:middle line:84%
of the past to
more sophisticated

00:02:27.314 --> 00:02:30.442 align:middle line:84%
electronic approaches, where you
literally manipulate the brain,

00:02:30.442 --> 00:02:32.444 align:middle line:84%
you manipulate the
behavior of people.

00:02:32.444 --> 00:02:34.279 align:middle line:84%
And what has been
discovered is that there

00:02:34.279 --> 00:02:37.074 align:middle line:84%
is what's called a frequency
following response, where

00:02:37.074 --> 00:02:39.826 align:middle line:84%
an external signal,
whether it be, say,

00:02:39.826 --> 00:02:42.829 align:middle line:84%
a radio signal or a
pulse-modulator radio

00:02:42.829 --> 00:02:46.500 align:middle line:84%
signal flickering light
at a certain flicker rate.

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:48.835 align:middle line:84%
Sound waves interacting
in a certain way

00:02:48.835 --> 00:02:50.754 align:middle line:84%
can drive the brain,
force the brain

00:02:50.754 --> 00:02:54.091 align:middle line:84%
into following that pattern,
frequency following response.

00:02:54.091 --> 00:02:57.511 align:middle line:84%
And so what happens is
those responses that

00:02:57.511 --> 00:03:03.850 align:middle line:84%
are associated with particular
emotions-- anger, calmness

00:03:03.850 --> 00:03:06.436 align:middle line:84%
or peacefulness--
you can manipulate

00:03:06.436 --> 00:03:08.688 align:middle line:84%
the overall sort
of brain activity

00:03:08.688 --> 00:03:10.190 align:middle line:90%
to push a person this way.

00:03:10.190 --> 00:03:12.567 align:middle line:84%
And you can use any
electromagnetic carrier

00:03:12.567 --> 00:03:13.485 align:middle line:90%
to achieve that end.

00:03:13.485 --> 00:03:15.070 align:middle line:84%
And that's just on
the emotional side.

00:03:15.070 --> 00:03:18.782 align:middle line:84%
As you get a higher resolution,
an ability to kind of

00:03:18.782 --> 00:03:20.784 align:middle line:90%
tune that more finely.

00:03:20.784 --> 00:03:23.412 align:middle line:84%
And there's a couple of
projects that I can mention

00:03:23.412 --> 00:03:24.538 align:middle line:90%
that are dealing with that.

00:03:24.538 --> 00:03:28.250 align:middle line:84%
There's some DARPA programs
now to look at the brain

00:03:28.250 --> 00:03:31.002 align:middle line:84%
to determine what a person
is actually thinking

00:03:31.002 --> 00:03:33.880 align:middle line:84%
and then create complex
signals, to take those patterns

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:36.133 align:middle line:84%
and impose them on another
to see if you can literally

00:03:36.133 --> 00:03:38.301 align:middle line:84%
transfer thought from
one person to another.

00:03:38.301 --> 00:03:42.305 align:middle line:84%
This is ongoing experimentation
of our government,

00:03:42.305 --> 00:03:44.808 align:middle line:84%
and it's kind of
mirroring what probably we

00:03:44.808 --> 00:03:46.852 align:middle line:90%
can do naturally in any case.

00:03:46.852 --> 00:03:51.565 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Nick, advertising has
really captured exactly what

00:03:51.565 --> 00:03:54.526 align:middle line:84%
you're talking about
in a scientific way.

00:03:54.526 --> 00:03:57.404 align:middle line:84%
They know exactly what
to put in a commercial,

00:03:57.404 --> 00:03:59.489 align:middle line:90%
how to stimulate somebody.

00:03:59.489 --> 00:04:02.075 align:middle line:84%
They know they know what
buttons to push, don't they?

00:04:02.075 --> 00:04:03.410 align:middle line:90%
>>BEGICH: Yeah, and they do it.

00:04:03.410 --> 00:04:04.536 align:middle line:90%
Because it's no regulation.

00:04:04.536 --> 00:04:06.037 align:middle line:84%
And so anyone who
studies psychology

00:04:06.037 --> 00:04:08.665 align:middle line:84%
in any of the major
institutes in the world

00:04:08.665 --> 00:04:10.584 align:middle line:84%
now understand frequency
following response.

00:04:10.584 --> 00:04:11.960 align:middle line:84%
So when you apply
to advertising,

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:14.838 align:middle line:84%
within 20, 30 seconds
you can create just

00:04:14.838 --> 00:04:16.798 align:middle line:84%
on a light effect,
just a flicker effect,

00:04:16.798 --> 00:04:18.048 align:middle line:90%
you can create an entrainment.

00:04:18.048 --> 00:04:20.051 align:middle line:84%
And so when you think
about-- think about people

00:04:20.051 --> 00:04:20.969 align:middle line:90%
in front of a TV set.

00:04:20.969 --> 00:04:22.804 align:middle line:84%
When your spouse
is cooking dinner

00:04:22.804 --> 00:04:24.723 align:middle line:84%
and they're hollering
at you, dinner is ready,

00:04:24.723 --> 00:04:29.561 align:middle line:84%
dinner is ready, and you're
in a very light trance state,

00:04:29.561 --> 00:04:30.353 align:middle line:90%
actually.

00:04:30.353 --> 00:04:32.564 align:middle line:84%
You're in a low
alpha, high theta

00:04:32.564 --> 00:04:35.525 align:middle line:84%
rate, which is where you're
highly suggestive, where you

00:04:35.525 --> 00:04:37.944 align:middle line:84%
can take in information
that sort of lines

00:04:37.944 --> 00:04:40.780 align:middle line:84%
up with what you think anyway,
and you just kind of move right

00:04:40.780 --> 00:04:41.573 align:middle line:90%
on.

00:04:41.573 --> 00:04:45.577 align:middle line:84%
So the 6 o'clock news becomes
an incredibly powerful tool

00:04:45.577 --> 00:04:47.037 align:middle line:90%
in terms of propaganda.

00:04:47.037 --> 00:04:48.872 align:middle line:84%
Advertising as such
becomes a tool.

00:04:48.872 --> 00:04:49.664 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: Huge.

00:04:49.664 --> 00:04:51.332 align:middle line:84%
>>BEGICH: And so when
you start to think

00:04:51.332 --> 00:04:54.169 align:middle line:84%
about just simple
manipulation like this

00:04:54.169 --> 00:04:57.172 align:middle line:84%
can move just enough
of a population

00:04:57.172 --> 00:04:59.925 align:middle line:84%
to maybe decide presidential
elections, as an example.

00:04:59.925 --> 00:05:02.761 align:middle line:84%
You've got these close,
close things that

00:05:02.761 --> 00:05:06.348 align:middle line:84%
happen in political arenas,
and just a little bit

00:05:06.348 --> 00:05:09.434 align:middle line:84%
of a push one way or the
other is really all it takes.

00:05:09.434 --> 00:05:11.269 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Do both
sides understand that,

00:05:11.269 --> 00:05:13.855 align:middle line:84%
I mean oppositions
in this stuff?

00:05:13.855 --> 00:05:16.233 align:middle line:84%
Because I know if I
were running a campaign

00:05:16.233 --> 00:05:18.276 align:middle line:84%
and I were the
candidate, I would

00:05:18.276 --> 00:05:21.947 align:middle line:84%
use everything
technologically I could

00:05:21.947 --> 00:05:26.159 align:middle line:84%
to manipulate the mind, to get
people to want to vote for you.

00:05:26.159 --> 00:05:28.912 align:middle line:84%
>>BEGICH: If the candidates
don't do it directly,

00:05:28.912 --> 00:05:30.372 align:middle line:90%
the consultants probably do.

00:05:30.372 --> 00:05:32.165 align:middle line:84%
And the reason I say
that is because you've

00:05:32.165 --> 00:05:32.957 align:middle line:90%
got a lot at stake.

00:05:32.957 --> 00:05:38.088 align:middle line:84%
People are spending millions on
ads, billions now on campaigns.

00:05:38.088 --> 00:05:40.799 align:middle line:84%
And so the amount of money
it takes to just layer

00:05:40.799 --> 00:05:42.717 align:middle line:84%
that up a little bit
is not that much.

00:05:42.717 --> 00:05:44.344 align:middle line:84%
And the idea of giving
people that kind

00:05:44.344 --> 00:05:45.637 align:middle line:84%
of happy, good
feeling when they're

00:05:45.637 --> 00:05:48.056 align:middle line:84%
seeing the ad, that's what you
want them to walk away with.

00:05:48.056 --> 00:05:49.849 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: Music is tied
into it, everything.

00:05:49.849 --> 00:05:50.267 align:middle line:90%
>>BEGICH: Right.

00:05:50.267 --> 00:05:52.394 align:middle line:84%
And now when you start
to think about taking it

00:05:52.394 --> 00:05:55.146 align:middle line:84%
from the old propaganda
and combining the tools,

00:05:55.146 --> 00:05:57.399 align:middle line:84%
like when you think about
internet, as an example--

00:05:57.399 --> 00:06:00.026 align:middle line:84%
internet is a way
to profile people

00:06:00.026 --> 00:06:01.611 align:middle line:90%
like we've never done before.

00:06:01.611 --> 00:06:04.072 align:middle line:84%
When you consider all the
things that are electronically

00:06:04.072 --> 00:06:07.117 align:middle line:84%
tracked and kept track of, and
these end up in data warehouse.

00:06:07.117 --> 00:06:08.535 align:middle line:84%
People say, oh,
it's not a problem.

00:06:08.535 --> 00:06:10.245 align:middle line:90%
We can't even sort that data.

00:06:10.245 --> 00:06:14.416 align:middle line:84%
Maybe not today, but we will
be able to sort that data.

00:06:14.416 --> 00:06:15.375 align:middle line:90%
And that's the point.

00:06:15.375 --> 00:06:19.254 align:middle line:84%
Storing it is valuable
inventory for the future.

00:06:19.254 --> 00:06:22.007 align:middle line:84%
As our resolution ability
to sort that data changes,

00:06:22.007 --> 00:06:24.759 align:middle line:84%
you're going to be able to
profile people so perfectly

00:06:24.759 --> 00:06:27.429 align:middle line:84%
and be able to tailor
ads directly for them.

00:06:27.429 --> 00:06:29.598 align:middle line:84%
I wrote about this 16
years ago in a book

00:06:29.598 --> 00:06:31.099 align:middle line:84%
called "Earth Rise
and Revolution,"

00:06:31.099 --> 00:06:32.017 align:middle line:90%
that this was coming.

00:06:32.017 --> 00:06:33.101 align:middle line:84%
Where they're going
to tailor ads--

00:06:33.101 --> 00:06:34.269 align:middle line:90%
>> NOORY: You were spot on.

00:06:34.269 --> 00:06:35.353 align:middle line:90%
>>BEGICH: And here we are.

00:06:35.353 --> 00:06:40.650 align:middle line:84%
And when you look at it, whether
it's on your smartphone or any

00:06:40.650 --> 00:06:44.487 align:middle line:84%
of your devices, the idea of
knowing that's you, number one,

00:06:44.487 --> 00:06:47.198 align:middle line:84%
identifying you as a
person, and then tying

00:06:47.198 --> 00:06:50.368 align:middle line:84%
the data that tells them sort
of where your frame of reference

00:06:50.368 --> 00:06:52.370 align:middle line:84%
is so they-- like in
a political campaign.

00:06:52.370 --> 00:06:53.413 align:middle line:90%
There's 99 issues.

00:06:53.413 --> 00:06:54.831 align:middle line:90%
One them you agree with.

00:06:54.831 --> 00:06:57.167 align:middle line:84%
That's the only one you're
going to hear in the future.

00:06:57.167 --> 00:07:00.295 align:middle line:84%
>> NOORY: I was watching some
advertisers look at a project

00:07:00.295 --> 00:07:02.088 align:middle line:84%
they were working
on technologically.

00:07:02.088 --> 00:07:05.133 align:middle line:84%
And they were doing research,
and it was just amazing.

00:07:05.133 --> 00:07:07.052 align:middle line:84%
They were showing
a car commercial

00:07:07.052 --> 00:07:10.555 align:middle line:84%
with an attractive woman
walking by the car,

00:07:10.555 --> 00:07:13.099 align:middle line:84%
kind of like touching the
sides of it and stuff.

00:07:13.099 --> 00:07:15.352 align:middle line:84%
And then they
researched guys who

00:07:15.352 --> 00:07:17.896 align:middle line:84%
were the buyers of
these kind of cars,

00:07:17.896 --> 00:07:20.523 align:middle line:84%
and none of them--
none of them--

00:07:20.523 --> 00:07:21.775 align:middle line:90%
knew what the car looked like.

00:07:21.775 --> 00:07:24.069 align:middle line:84%
They remembered the
name of the car,

00:07:24.069 --> 00:07:25.779 align:middle line:90%
and they remember the girl.

00:07:25.779 --> 00:07:28.239 align:middle line:84%
But they don't remember
the car at all, other

00:07:28.239 --> 00:07:31.326 align:middle line:84%
than it was a car
with this brand name.

00:07:31.326 --> 00:07:35.205 align:middle line:84%
And they said this was
a very successful test.

00:07:35.205 --> 00:07:37.040 align:middle line:84%
And that's what they
ran with for that ad.

00:07:37.040 --> 00:07:37.832 align:middle line:90%
>>BEGICH: Right.

00:07:37.832 --> 00:07:39.918 align:middle line:84%
Now, even more
sophisticated testing

00:07:39.918 --> 00:07:43.880 align:middle line:84%
would be to hook the
viewers up to EEGs

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:46.675 align:middle line:84%
and look at what's going
on within the brain

00:07:46.675 --> 00:07:48.635 align:middle line:84%
as they're watching
the ad in real time.

00:07:48.635 --> 00:07:50.470 align:middle line:84%
Now, they do this
with gaming now,

00:07:50.470 --> 00:07:53.515 align:middle line:84%
because the idea is they want
the game, through the light

00:07:53.515 --> 00:07:56.935 align:middle line:84%
and sound effects, to stimulate
the same portions of the brain

00:07:56.935 --> 00:07:59.479 align:middle line:84%
that are associated with
addictive behaviors,

00:07:59.479 --> 00:08:02.565 align:middle line:84%
sexual activity, the kinds of
things that highly stimulate

00:08:02.565 --> 00:08:08.363 align:middle line:84%
the brain, release endorphins
and brain chemicals that just

00:08:08.363 --> 00:08:10.407 align:middle line:84%
excite the heck
out of the person.

00:08:10.407 --> 00:08:15.120 align:middle line:84%
And what you see is that kind of
addictive behavior manifesting

00:08:15.120 --> 00:08:15.912 align:middle line:90%
in gaming.

00:08:15.912 --> 00:08:18.623 align:middle line:84%
Because it's
designed to do that.

00:08:18.623 --> 00:08:20.582 align:middle line:84%
That is what it's
supposed to do,

00:08:20.582 --> 00:08:24.003 align:middle line:84%
because they want to sell
millions of these units.

00:08:24.003 --> 00:08:26.297 align:middle line:84%
And the way they do them
is exactly this way.

00:08:26.297 --> 00:08:29.843 align:middle line:84%
So whether it's the advertising
or the device itself

00:08:29.843 --> 00:08:31.761 align:middle line:84%
that you're interacting
with-- virtual reality

00:08:31.761 --> 00:08:34.389 align:middle line:84%
is another place where
this will be applied.

00:08:34.389 --> 00:08:37.433 align:middle line:84%
And I mean, when you start to
think about just the direction

00:08:37.433 --> 00:08:39.059 align:middle line:84%
in which all of these
things are going,

00:08:39.059 --> 00:08:42.188 align:middle line:84%
the idea of manipulating
what's going

00:08:42.188 --> 00:08:46.151 align:middle line:84%
on within a brain for
nefarious purposes,

00:08:46.151 --> 00:08:47.152 align:middle line:90%
everyone can see that.

00:08:47.152 --> 00:08:49.237 align:middle line:84%
And everybody goes, ah,
what do we do about that?

00:08:49.237 --> 00:08:51.072 align:middle line:84%
But if you flip it
around-- and this

00:08:51.072 --> 00:08:55.076 align:middle line:84%
is where my research led me that
that was the most surprising,

00:08:55.076 --> 00:08:58.580 align:middle line:84%
is that when you flip this
around, what you find out

00:08:58.580 --> 00:09:00.039 align:middle line:84%
is that what they
really discovered

